note.subjective: New patient seen for alcohol use. Patient reports drinking 4x per week and having 3-4 drinks when he drinks, although he stated that he sometimes drinks an entire bottle in one sitting. He states that he often drinks at home in the evenings with the goal of unwinding and sometimes when he is feeling down. He reports being aware that his PCP is concerned about his drinking and that he feels guilty sometimes after drinking. He was able to identify that having alcohol in the house was related to the amount that he drinks
note.objective: Provided psychoeducation on healthy drinking limits and used motivational interviewing regarding his desire to cut back or eliminate his drinking. He was able to identify some alternative stress reducing activities and rated his overall motivation as a 8 out of 10.
note.assessment: Patient seems to be at the contemplation stage regarding his alcohol use. Making statements about a desire to reduce his drinking. He reported that the information provided was interesting and novel information.
note.plan: Patient to return to clinic next week to continue discussion of decreasing his alcohol use and relaxation.

note.subjective: Client reports drinking at least 4 times a week, usually having 3-4 drinks, and sometimes drinking more than intended. Client feels guilty about drinking and wants to cut back. Client uses drinking to unwind and relax, especially when feeling down. Client reports depression and notes that drinking makes it worse.
note.objective: Client appears calm and cooperative during the session. Client's speech is clear and coherent.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report of excessive drinking and feelings of guilt, it is likely that the client is experiencing risky alcohol use. The client's drinking habits may be contributing to their depression, and reducing drinking could help alleviate symptoms.
note.plan: Short-term goal: Client will aim to cut back to 2 drinks per night. Client will reduce wine availability at home and explore alternative relaxation techniques (reading, watching movies, taking baths). Client will return for a follow-up session to discuss progress. Long-term goal: Client will work towards reducing overall drinking habits to minimize health risks and alleviate depression symptoms.

note.subjective: Client reports drinking alcohol at least four times a week, with an average of three to four drinks per session, primarily wine. Client drinks to unwind at home, often while watching movies or taking a bath. Client expresses feelings of guilt for drinking more than intended on occasion and sometimes finishes a bottle in one night. Client acknowledges that drinking sometimes makes depression worse and is interested in cutting back to two drinks a night.
note.objective: Client appeared engaged and responsive during the session. Client's mood was stable, and affect was appropriate. Client demonstrated insight into the relationship between alcohol consumption and depression. Client reported a readiness level of 8 out of 10 to cut back on drinking.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report of frequent alcohol consumption and its impact on depression, the client may be at risk for alcohol use disorder and exacerbation of depressive symptoms. The client's willingness to reduce alcohol intake suggests a readiness for behavioral change.
note.plan: Short-term goal: Client will aim to reduce alcohol consumption to two drinks per night. Strategies include reducing the amount of wine available at home and exploring alternative relaxation methods such as reading, watching movies, and taking baths without alcohol. Long-term goal: Continue to monitor and reduce alcohol intake to within safe limits and assess the impact on depressive symptoms. Schedule a follow-up session in a few weeks to evaluate progress and adjust the plan as needed.

note.subjective: Client is a male presenting to therapy for alcohol use. He reports he often drinks alcohol two to three times a week, only on the weekends. Client reports he also has five or six beers when he goes out with friends. Therapist provided client with guidelines for men which state that men can drink up to 14 drinks a week or four on one occasion and be considered low risk. Client feels his drinking is not problematic. Client stated "Well, I don't consider my drinking binge drinking". Upon hearing the information, client feels he has a lot to think about regarding the way he views his drinking habits. He states that he likes the way beer tastes and the way it makes him feel. However, upon hearing the risks, client reports he now has to think about his drinking.
note.objective: In the beginning of the session, client appeared reluctant to engage in therapy session. However, upon talking with therapist, he appears to open up more and is leaning towards reconsidering his drinking habits.
note.assessment: Initially, during the beginning of therapy session, client appears to be in the pre-contemplation stage of change. This was evident with the fact that client felt his drinking was normal and not problematic. However, upon getting information from therapist, client appears to lean more towards contemplation stage of change. This was evident as on one hand, client feels he enjoys drinking, the way it tastes and makes him feel. On the other hand, he also feels he has to think about potential health risks associated with excessive drinking.
note.plan: Client will follow up with therapist for a three month follow up appointment to talk about ADHD as well as check in on his alcohol use.

note.subjective: Client reports drinking alcohol 2-3 days a week, typically having 5-6 drinks on each occasion. Client does not consider their drinking to be a problem, but is open to discussing the potential health risks. Client likes the taste and social aspect of drinking, but is concerned about the potential long-term health consequences.
note.objective: Client appears calm and cooperative during the session. Client's speech is clear and coherent, and they maintain good eye contact. Client's body language is relaxed, and they do not appear to be under the influence of alcohol during the session.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report of frequent and heavy alcohol use, they may be at risk for developing an alcohol use disorder. The client's lack of awareness about the health risks associated with their drinking pattern is a concern. However, the client's willingness to discuss their drinking and consider the potential consequences is a positive indicator.
note.plan: Short-term goals include educating the client about the risks associated with binge drinking and encouraging them to consider reducing their alcohol intake. Long-term goals include reducing the client's risk of developing an alcohol use disorder and improving their overall health and well-being. The therapist will follow up with the client in three months to reassess their drinking habits and provide ongoing support and guidance as needed.

note.subjective: Client reports using alcohol two to three days a week, typically on weekends, consuming five to six drinks per occasion. Client expresses enjoyment of drinking beer and its role in social life but acknowledges potential health risks after discussing them with the therapist. Client is unsure about making changes to drinking habits but indicates that experiencing negative health consequences might prompt a change.
note.objective: Client appeared engaged and responsive during the discussion about alcohol use. Client's mood was stable, and affect was appropriate. Speech was clear and coherent. No observable signs of intoxication or withdrawal symptoms.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report of consuming five to six drinks on two to three days a week, the client's drinking pattern meets the criteria for binge drinking. The client is at risk for both short-term and long-term health consequences associated with binge drinking, including accidents, heart disease, cancer, liver problems, and mental health issues. The client is currently ambivalent about changing drinking habits but is open to considering the risks.
note.plan: Provide the client with educational materials on risky drinking, its consequences, and signs of alcohol use disorder. Schedule a three-month follow-up appointment to discuss ADHD and check in on alcohol use. Encourage the client to reflect on the potential health risks and consider making changes to drinking habits. Short-term goal: Increase client's awareness of the risks associated with current drinking patterns. Long-term goal: Support the client in making informed decisions about alcohol use and reducing potential health risks.

note.subjective: Client is a male who is presenting to therapy due to issues with his weight. He reports struggling with his weight recently. He was able to lose 5 pounds but ended up gaining it back. He initially felt great and proud of himself. Client went on to tell therapist how he was able to lose weight, including decreasing the amount he ate, eating more fruits and vegetables and walking 20 minutes daily. In addition, client reports he was drinking four to six glasses of orange juice a day. Therapist informed client that fruit juice isn't necessarily healthy and can contain just as many calories as a can of soda. Upon talking with the therapist, client became of aware of what caused him to gain weight. Client was able to identify steps to take to cut back on drinking fruit juice such as asking his wife not to buy it and replacing it with water or a low calorie drink. He reports being motivated to make the necessary changes to lose the weight.
note.objective: Client initially appears disappointed with himself for losing the weight and gaining it right back. He now appears to be highly motivated to follow through with his plan regarding losing weight.
note.assessment: Client appears to be in the preparation stage of change. He appears aware and highly motivated to make the changes in order to lose weight. He has demonstrated awareness regarding the impact that drinking fruit juice has on his diet and how it has contributed to his weight gain.
note.plan: Client will return to meet with therapist in two weeks. He will decrease the amount of fruit juice he is drinking.

note.subjective: Client reports struggling with weight loss, having lost 5 pounds but then gaining it back. He feels great and proud of himself when he loses weight, but gives up when he gains it back. He has been eating more fruits and vegetables, including 4-6 glasses of orange juice a day, and walking 20 minutes a day.
note.objective: Client appears motivated to lose weight, but may be unaware of the high calorie content of fruit juice. He is willing to make changes to his diet and exercise routine.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report of weight loss and gain, and his observable motivation to make changes, it appears that he may be struggling with unhealthy eating habits and lack of knowledge about nutrition. The client's reliance on fruit juice as a healthy option may be contributing to his weight gain.
note.plan: Short-term goals: Reduce daily fruit juice intake, replace with low-calorie drinks or water, and continue walking 20 minutes a day. Long-term goals: Develop a personalized approach to nutrition, improve overall health and well-being, and reduce symptoms of weight-related issues. Next session will focus on reviewing progress, addressing any obstacles, and providing ongoing support and guidance.

note.subjective: John reports struggling with weight loss, having lost 5 pounds but then regaining it. He mentions feeling proud and better when he lost weight but became discouraged when he gained it back. He attributes the weight gain to increased fruit and vegetable intake, particularly consuming four to six glasses of orange juice daily. He expresses a desire to cut back on fruit juice but acknowledges his love for it. He rates his confidence in reducing juice intake as a six or seven out of ten.
note.objective: John appears engaged and willing to discuss his weight issues. He shows understanding of the impact of his diet on his weight and health. He demonstrates a moderate level of confidence in making dietary changes, rating it a six or seven out of ten initially, but later expressing full confidence (ten out of ten) after discussing strategies.
note.assessment: John's weight fluctuations are likely due to excessive fruit juice consumption, which he was unaware contains high calories. He shows motivation to make changes and understands the importance of reducing juice intake for weight loss and overall health. His confidence in making these changes improved during the session.
note.plan: Short-term: John will aim to eliminate fruit juice from his diet and replace it with sugar-free drinks or water. He will ask his wife not to buy fruit juice to reduce temptation. Long-term: Continue monitoring weight and dietary habits, focusing on sustainable lifestyle changes to support weight loss and overall health. Follow-up in two weeks to assess progress and adjust the plan as needed.

note.subjective: The client is a male who is presenting to therapy due to his wife wanting him to improve his health and eating habits. Client reports he feels fine and doesn't see an issue with his health. Client stated "I really don't see what the big problem is".
note.objective: Client reports he feels fine and doesn't have any issues regarding his physical health. Client does report he often eats out a lot due to his job being labor intensive and not being able to make it home to eat.
note.assessment: Client appears to be in the pre-contemplation stage of change as evident with him not thinking about changing his behaviors. He appears to defend his unhealthy eating habits and does not feel that it is a problem.
note.plan: Client was given information on obesity and diabetes.

note.subjective: The client reports feeling fine and not seeing a problem with his health habits, despite his wife's concerns. He mentions working manual labor-intensive jobs and sweating out 'bad things' he puts in his system. He has noticed a slight weight gain but does not feel bloated. He last visited the doctor for a physical about a year ago and everything was fine.
note.objective: The client appears to be in a defensive stance regarding his health habits, attributing his wife's concerns to her love and desire for him to live a long time. He seems to be downplaying the potential risks associated with his eating habits and physical activity level. His speech patterns are somewhat dismissive and casual when discussing his health.
note.assessment: The client's lack of concern about his health habits and his tendency to downplay potential risks may indicate a lack of awareness or understanding of the importance of healthy habits. His wife's concerns may be valid, and it is possible that the client is at risk for developing health problems such as obesity or diabetes. Further education and exploration of the client's health habits and attitudes may be necessary.
note.plan: Provide the client with information on obesity and diabetes, and explore his willingness to make changes to his health habits. Discuss the importance of regular health check-ups and encourage him to schedule a follow-up appointment with his doctor. Consider involving the client's wife in future sessions to address her concerns and work together to develop a plan for supporting the client's health goals.

note.subjective: The client reports feeling fine and does not see his health habits as a significant concern. He mentions that his wife has been urging him to improve his health habits, which he finds unnecessary. The client works a manual labor-intensive job and often eats out at restaurants like Applebee's due to his work schedule. He has noticed a slight weight gain but does not feel bloated. The client had a physical last year, and everything was reported as fine. He acknowledges his wife's concern but feels that eating out helps him cope with his demanding job.
note.objective: The client appears to be in good spirits and does not exhibit any observable signs of distress or physical discomfort. His speech is coherent and his mood is stable. He is open to discussing his health habits and the concerns raised by his wife.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report, he does not perceive his health habits as problematic despite his wife's concerns. His manual labor job and occasional weight gain suggest potential health risks, but he does not show immediate signs of distress. The client's willingness to discuss health information indicates a level of openness to addressing potential issues.
note.plan: Short-term: Provide the client with information on obesity and diabetes to increase his awareness of potential health risks. Encourage open communication with his wife about his health habits and the importance of maintaining a balanced diet. Long-term: Work on developing healthier coping mechanisms for stress related to his job. Encourage regular check-ups with his doctor and discuss strategies for maintaining a healthy lifestyle despite his demanding work schedule.

note.subjective: Client is a male who has been in therapy for six weeks. Client is presenting to therapy for alcohol use and criminal behaviors. Client is mostly influenced by alcohol and his peers. When client meets with friends, he starts drinking and engages in negative, criminal behaviors. Client's goals are to attend school, maintain relationship with his significant other and work on his negative behaviors/peer influences. Client reports he recently went to Polytech and was able to obtain forms to complete. Client reports his girlfriend helped him complete the forms and he needs to return them. Client discussed the support and loyalty he gets from his significant other Donna. Client reports she is a positive influence and helps keep him on track. Client also discussed how he enjoys hanging with peers-even though he engages in drinking and negative behaviors. Client stated "I like to just have a bit of fun." Client is also torn between spending time with his friends and significant other at times.
note.objective: Client reports he engages in destructive behavior while under the influence of alcohol and hanging with his peers.
note.assessment: Client appears to be in the contemplation stage of change. Client appears torn between his peers and significant other at times. Client has made some progress since the last session. Client was able to complete school paperwork with his girlfriend's help. In addition, client is able to stay on track when he is with his girlfriend.
note.plan: Client's goals are to turn in school paperwork, build upon his current relationship with Donna and work on decreasing negative behaviors. Client will also work on establishing boundaries with his peers and eliminate feelings of guilt.

note.subjective: The client reports feeling more confident and motivated since starting therapy. He attributes this to having someone to talk to and feeling busy. He has made progress in taking steps towards his goals, such as going to the polytech and getting forms. He expresses a desire to lead a life free from offending and to have a job and a family with his partner Donna.
note.objective: The client appears more engaged and motivated during the session. He is able to reflect on his progress and identify areas where he needs support. He maintains eye contact and is able to articulate his thoughts and feelings.
note.assessment: The client is making progress towards his goals, but still struggles with the temptation to offend, particularly when drinking with his friends. He recognizes the importance of having a support system, such as Donna, to help him stay on track. He is torn between his desire to spend time with his friends and his commitment to leading a life free from offending.
note.plan: Short-term goals: The client will deliver the forms to the polytech by the end of the week. He will continue to work on building his confidence and motivation. Long-term goals: The client will develop strategies to manage his temptations to offend, particularly when drinking with his friends. He will work on building a support system that will help him stay on track with his goals. The client will explore ways to spend time with his friends that do not involve offending.

note.subjective: Client reports that the sessions have been helpful, particularly in providing someone to talk to and keep him busy. He mentions making progress with enrolling in polytech, including getting forms and seeking help from a friend named Donna. Client expresses feelings of guilt for not spending time with friends and acknowledges that drinking makes it easier for him to offend. He also mentions a desire to have a job and a life with his girlfriend, Donna, and that offending does not fit into this vision.
note.objective: Client appeared engaged and responsive during the session. He was punctual and showed signs of progress in his actions, such as obtaining forms for polytech and seeking help with them. Client's mood was stable, and he was able to articulate his thoughts and feelings clearly. He expressed a sense of guilt and conflict regarding his friendships and offending behavior.
note.assessment: Based on the client's report and observable progress, it appears that he is making positive strides towards his goals. He has shown initiative in pursuing education and has identified key areas of concern, such as his tendency to offend when under the influence of alcohol. The client's feelings of guilt and conflict suggest a desire to change his behavior and align his actions with his long-term goals. However, he still faces challenges in resisting peer pressure and managing his relationships with friends.
note.plan: Short-term goals include continuing to support the client in submitting his polytech forms and exploring ways to manage his drinking and peer pressure. Encourage the client to communicate his goals and boundaries with his friends and seek their support. Long-term goals involve helping the client develop healthier coping mechanisms and strengthening his relationships with positive influences, such as Donna. Additionally, explore resources at the polytech that can assist with reading and writing challenges. Schedule follow-up sessions to monitor progress and provide ongoing support.
